\begin{definition}[Recursive Equations] \label{def:norec}
A \emph{recursive equation} is a term of the form
%
$$
|x == V^[lam y e]| \quad \text{where}\ x \in \freevars{e}
% |x == V^[lam y E^[x]]| \quad \text{where}\ x \in \freevars{e}
$$
\simon{We changed this back to match the defn in 4.1.} \ranjit{ACK}
%
where the LHS is a variable and the RHS is a \emph{value}
that is or contains a $\lambda$ in which $|x|$ occurs free.
%
A term $e$ is \emph{recursive} if it contains a recursive equation.
%
A term $e$ is \emph{transitively recursive} if $\rsteps{\rr}{e}{e'}$ where $e'$ is recursive.
%
A term $e$ has \emph{\norecursion} if it is \emph{not} transitively recursive.
\end{definition}
Our main confluence theorem is as follows:

\begin{theorem}[Confluence] \label{thm:confluence}
%
If $e$ has \norecursion and $\rsteps{\rr}{e}{e_1}$ and $\rsteps{\rr}{e}{e_2}$ then $\join{\rr}{e_1}{e_2}$.
%
% The reduction relation $\rr$ is confluent for all terms with \norecursion.
%
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
%
First, we partition $\rr$ into the relations $\runi \cup \rcon$, $\rapp$, $\rgc$ and $\rspc$.
%
Next, we show that each of these relations is confluent and pairwise
commutative (\cref{fig:confluence-summary}).
%
Finally, we use \cref{lem:comm-n} to prove their union $\rr$ is confluent.
\end{proof}

In the rest of the proof we assume that we are working with terms with \norecursion.
The condition is only need to prove $\runi$ is confluent,
but we assume it globally for clarity.

\subsection{Disjointness, Reduction under, and the Diamond property}

In talking about confluence we often speak of two different reduction steps with a common
starting point, thus $\rstep{\rr}{e}{e_1}$ and $\rstep{\rr}{e}{e_2}$.
In the first of these there is a sub-term of $e$, say $\Delta_1$, that is the actual redex;
the root of $\Delta_1$ matches some rule in $\rr$.  $\Delta_1$ is just an ordinary
expression, but we use the notation ``$\Delta$'' to stress that it is the root of a redex
(see \cref{fig:notation}).
%
$\Delta_1$ is a sub-term of $e$ (or possibly $\Delta = e$),
which we write $\Delta_1 \occunder e$ (again in \cref{fig:notation}).
%
Note that $e_1 \occunder e_2$ is equivalent to saying that there exists some expression
context $E$ such that $E[e_1] \equiv e_2$, \ie that $e_2$ can be decomposed into a context
$E$ whose hole is filled by $e_1$.

Similarly we may identify $\Delta_2$, the redex that is reduced by $\rstep{\rr}{e}{e_2}$.
Now there are two cases to consider:
\begin{enumerate}
\item $\Delta_1$ is disjoint from $\Delta_2$ in $e$; or
\item $\Delta_1 \occunder \Delta_2$, or $\Delta_2 \occunder \Delta_1$.
\end{enumerate}
%
\simon{What if $\Delta_1 = \Delta_2$?} \ranjit{ACK: $\occunder$ includes that, let me change to clarify}
%
One might wonder if $\Delta_1$ can \emph{overlap} $\Delta_2$, but that is not possible:
we are discussing syntax trees, not graphs, and so for distinct $\Delta_1$ and $\Delta_2$,
either the root of $\Delta_1$ is a child of the root of $\Delta_2$, or vice versa, or neither.

In the first case (a) we have the diamond property immediately:
\begin{lemma}[Disjoint] \label{lem:disjoint}
Let $e \equiv \ldots \rdx{1} \ldots \rdx{2} \ldots$
be an expression with two \emph{disjoint} redexes
$\rdx{1}$ and $\rdx{2}$.
%
If $\rstep{}{e}{\ldots \rdx{1}' \ldots \rdx{2} \ldots \equiv e_1}$ and
   $\rstep{}{e}{ \ldots \rdx{1} \ldots \rdx{2}' \ldots \equiv e_2}$
then there exists $e'$ such that
		$\rstep{}{e_1}{e'}$ and
		$\rstep{}{e_2}{e'}$.
\end{lemma}
\simon{What is a ``reduct''?  Same as ``redex''?  Say so.} \ranjit{ACK: reduct is "redex" plus thing it steps to, so here we just want "redex}

\begin{proof}
Trivial: $e' = \ldots \rdx{1}' \ldots \rdx{2}' \ldots$.
\end{proof}
\noindent
So to prove the diamond property for a relation $\rr$, we should focus attention
only on case (b).

\subsection{Lemmas for Reductions-Under} \label{sec:under-lemmas}

\simon{Badly needs an intro sentence or two.  What is ``reductions under''?  I can't even parse the statement of Lemma B.5!} \ranjit{ACK: check}

Next, we prove a set of ``reductions-under'' $R$ lemmas that say that
%
if a term $e$ can be
%
(1)~reduced using two different rules $R$ and $S$ as $\rstep{R}{e}{e_R}$ and $\rstep{S}{e_S}$, such that
%
(2)~the redex for the $S$ reduction is a \emph{sub-term} of the redex for the $R$ reduction,
%
then there exists some $e'$ such that
%
$e_R$ (resp. $e_S$) can be reduced to $e'$ using some number of $S$ (resp. $R$) reductions.
%
These lemmas will be used to prove that two relations $R$ and $S$ commute \eg have the diamond
property, by splitting cases on which relation is the ``outer'' reduction and which is the ``inner''
and then applying the appropriate ``reduction-under'' lemma for the outer relation, and using
\cref{lem:disjoint} for the case where the redexes are disjoint.


\subsubsection{Application}

