The following lemma says that
%
if a term $\rdx{\rapp}$ is the root of an $\rapp$ reduction $\rstep{\rapp}{\rdx{\rapp}}{\rdx{\rapp}'}$
%
and the $\rdx{\rapp}$ additionally contains under it a \emph{subterm} $\rdx{}$
that is the root of some $\rr$ reduction $\rstep{\rr}{\rdx{}}{\rdx{}'}$
%
then it is possible to join the result of the $\rr$ and $\rapp$ reduction at a
common term $\rdx{\rapp}''$ by executing a single step of the \emph{other} reduction,
\ie $\rapp$ and $\rr$ respectively.
%
(Recall that $E[e'] \equiv e$ means that $e' \occunder e$ \ie $e'$ occurs under or is a sub-term of $e$).

\begin{lemma}[Under-$\rapp$] \label{lem:under-a}
If $\rstep{\rapp}{\rdx{\rapp}}{\rdx{\rapp}'}$ and
   $\rdx{\rapp} \equiv E[\rdx{}]$ and
   $\rstep{\rr}{\rdx{}}{\rdx{}'}$
then there exists $\rdx{\rapp}''$ such that
   $\rstep{\rr}{\rdx{\rapp}'}{\rdx{\rapp}''}$ and
   $\rstep{\rapp}{E[\rdx{}']}{\rdx{\rapp}''}$.
