We can now prove that any two $\runik$ reductions (and hence $\runi$ reductions) can be joined.

\begin{lemma}[$\runik$-join] \label{lem:uk-join}
If $\rsteps{\runib{i}}{e}{e_i}$ and $\rsteps{\runib{j}}{e}{e_j}$
then there exists $e'$ such that $\rsteps{\runi}{e_i, e_j}{e'}$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Let $k = \max(i, j)$.
%
As $\runib{i}, \runib{j} \subseteq \runib{k}$ we have
$\rsteps{\runib{k}}{e}{e_i}$ and $\rsteps{\runib{k}}{e}{e_j}$.
%
By \cref{lem:uk-term} and \cref{lem:uk-lc} and \cref{lem:local},
$\runib{k}$ is confluent, hence there exists $e'$ such that
$\rsteps{\runib{k}}{e_i, e_j}{e'}$, after which $\runib{k} \subseteq \runi$
completes the proof.
